{
  "text": "In a recent study it has been shown that after food intake, the rapid glucose-independent preabsorptive rise of insulin is absent in rats provided with functional neonatal pancreas transplants [CITATION_1] . The present results confirm these findings. The transplants secreted insulin within one minute after intravenous glucose stimulation [CITATION_2] . As presented elsewhere, histology and electron microscopy of these transplanted pancreases showed vascularized clusters of well granulated B cells. After transplantation there were 1%-2% of stained B cells left from the original pancreas [CITATION_3] . This has been confirmed by others [CITATION_4] . Since blood glucose and plasma insulin levels of sham operated diabetic rats varied after meal ingestion from 27 to 31 mmol/1 and 0 to 3 mU/1 respectively, it is unlikely that the original pancreas secreted significant amounts of insulin [CITATION_5] .",
